{{Mergeto|Algae fuel|date=May 2018}} '''Seaweed fuel''' or '''seaweed oil''' is an alternative to liquid [[fossil fuel]]s that uses [[seaweed]] as its source of energy-rich oils. Like fossil fuel, seaweed fuel releases {{CO2}} when burnt, but unlike fossil fuel, algae fuel and other biofuels only release {{CO2}} recently removed from the atmosphere via photosynthesis as the seaweed or plant grew.
Seaweed does not require [[fresh water]] and can as such be grown in the sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novozymes.com/en/news/news-archive/2012/01/from-seaweed-to-biofuels|title=A new research collaboration between Novozymes and Sea6 Energy will explore enzymatic technology to produce fuel ethanol, fine chemicals, and protein from seaweed|author=|date=|website=www.novozymes.com|accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref>
==Fuels== Seaweed can be converted into various types of fuels, depending on the technique and the part of the cells used. Also, using techniques such as fast [[hydrothermal liquefaction]], oil yield for the seaweed can be increased.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.algal.2014.05.009 |title=Fast hydrothermal liquefaction of a Norwegian macro-alga: Screening tests |journal=Algal Research |volume=6 |pages=271–276 |year=2014 |last1=Bach |first1=Quang-Vu |last2=Sillero |first2=Miguel Valcuende |last3=Tran |first3=Khanh-Quang |last4=Skjermo |first4=Jorunn }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/articles/2014/10/turning-humble-seaweed-to-biofuel.html|title=Turning Humble Seaweed to Biofuel|author=|date=|website=www.renewableenergyworld.com|accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref>
===Biodiesel=== {{Main article|Biodiesel}} [[Transesterification]] of seaweed oil (into biodiesel) is possible with species such as ''[[Chaetomorpha linum]]'', ''[[Ulva lactuca]]'', ''[[Enteromorpha compressa]]'' (''[[Ulva]]'').<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3390/en7117194|title=Macroalgae-Derived Biofuel: A Review of Methods of Energy Extraction from Seaweed Biomass|journal=Energies|volume=7|issue=11|pages=7194–7222|year=2014|last1=Milledge|first1=John|last2=Smith|first2=Benjamin|last3=Dyer|first3=Philip|last4=Harvey|first4=Patricia}}</ref>{{rs inline|date=August 2018}}
==Ethanol and butanol== Following species are being investigated as suitable species for producing [[ethanol]] and/or [[butanol]] from: * ''[[Alaria esculenta]]'' * ''[[Laminaria saccharina]]'' * ''[[Palmaria palmata]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/articles/2013/06/from-the-beach-to-the-pump-is-kelp-a-viable-biofuel.html|title=From the Sea to the Pump: Is Kelp a Viable Biofuel?|author=|date=|website=www.renewableenergyworld.com|accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://www.theecologist.org/green_green_living/2988214/biofuels_from_seaweed.html SAMS MacroFuels project using species such as dabberlocks, sugar kelp and dulse]</ref>
